today, a group of guys came into rustic. while i was sweeping they started talking to me and told me they were from florida. we found out one of them went to stoneman douglas. my mom told one of his friends that my cousin didn‚Äôt make it. turns out the guy who graduated, kenny, was really good friends with meadow. i had a 30 minute conversation with him as if i had known him forever. we talked about how everyone loved her and how he keeps a picture of her in his pocket every day. he was at the service and saw me speak and didn‚Äôt even know it was me. we talked about how hard it was but how we‚Äôre all trying to be strong and live every day happy and with a positive attitude. but how we wish we could go back and change something about that day and how it‚Äôs a day none of us will ever recover from fully. both of us ended up crying. more than anything, it‚Äôs absolutely insane that these guys came across the country to a state like idaho and ended up in my family‚Äôs restaurant and i happened to be sweeping and the guy happened to ask me, of all the employees, a question. i‚Äôm not religious or anything but the world works in crazy ways and some things just really happened for a reason. this day will stick with me. and no day goes by without feeling the weight of what happened. but anyways always remember to hug the ones you love and appreciate every small thing in life and everyone around you. thanks for reading.

Pretty fucked up if you think about how most men who commit sexual assault will never be held accountable for their actions. How they get to walk through this world acting as though they did nothing wrong. How they can present themselves outwardly as good boys and worthy of respect. How they can trust that we will accept the narratives that they put forth. And we do.
Sometimes I Instagram stalk the girlfriend of the boy who tried to rape me in high school. I knew her rather well. It makes me so angry that she will never know what he did to me. Assuming he‚Äôs kind to her, respectful of her boundaries, she‚Äôs probably better off not knowing. Happier.
Maybe they‚Äôll get married or maybe they won‚Äôt. Either way he‚Äôll probably be married someday. He‚Äôll be the center of someone‚Äôs universe. Maybe they‚Äôll have kids. Maybe even a daughter. Her dad will be her hero. She may never have a reason to think otherwise.
Sometimes I think about texting her. Or texting him. Asking her if she knows what he did. Asking him if he knows what he did. Asking him if he can even begin to try to comprehend the gravity of his actions.
It could have been worse. He could have jumped out of a bush and raped me in a dark alley. He could have done to me what others view as legitimate sexual assault. But just because I invited him over, just because I wasn‚Äôt penetrated, doesn‚Äôt make it okay. I was too young to understand what was happening. To understand that what happened was not my fault.
After I finally told my mom, she told me not to tell anyone. For my sake, because being sexually assaulted is something that would cause me to ‰∏¢ËÑ∏ (lose face). But also for his. Because it would ‚Äúembarrass‚Äù him. Because such a punishment would not fit the crime. Because it would be too harsh.
Even to this day my mom sometimes asks about him. I tell her time and time again that I don‚Äôt want to talk about the boy who tried to rape me. She tells me that it wasn‚Äôt that big of a deal. That I shouldn‚Äôt use that word. She presses me for details.
He lives in New York City. His parents bought him an apartment and a Steinway piano. He has a girlfriend. She loves him. And she will never know what he did.

Trigger Warning: Rape and Sexual Assault (Same post as Facebook, but need to say it on here, too)
As a 20 year old woman, I am grieving today. Dr. Christine Blasey Ford's testimony crushed me because of its familiarity. I've heard those words too many times whether I was wrapped up in a blanket on the couch back home, sitting with someone across the table, or reading the text message. It is a feeling like swallowing a rock when multiple of your closest friends confide in you about their experiences with sexual assault and rape. Sometimes I was across the country when it happened. Sometimes I was at the same party.
Social backlash is the main reason why none of my friends reported the incidents. We live in a society that conditions women to be careful and be quiet, to string our pain up in loops and lock it in a drawer for years instead of taking administrative/legal action. Do not rush yourself. Do not feel pressured to speak out at all. Do not feel pressured to hold your tongue. Coping with pain is a process.
It is imperative that we recognize sexism in its most subtle forms. Stop speaking to us as if we're children. Stop lashing out on us. Stop projecting your insecurities and emotional pain onto us. Stop conditioning us to accept sloppy, half-hearted forms of love.
I am thankful for Dr. Ford's courage for recounting one of the most traumatic experiences of her life on an international stage. I am also grateful for the resiliency of the women in my life: my mom, my grandmother, my aunts, my teammates, my sorority, and my friends as we push against these gender barriers. I still love you. I am still here. I am still proud of you.

Please, register to vote and get your absentee ballot in so we never APPOINT or ELECT a PERPETRATOR OF SEXUAL ASSAULT again.

The world is a little bit duller today as we lost such a beautiful soul. My Papou has been an inspiration to me and my family for the past 83 years of his life. His last few weeks were challenging but I will always remember the selfless, kind hearted, strong, and witty man we all knew and loved. His whole life was dedicated to our family and these past 20 years have been all about being there for his grandkids. As we visited his hospital room on New Year's Day he still bantered with my Yiayia as she tried to get his wallet out to give us all money for no reason at all, and then sat up in his chair snapping and singing along to Greek music. I'll miss our trips to dairy queen, the time we spent together in Greece, the annoying clang of his komboloi when he broke too fast in the car, the years of debating what side of the gym he should sit on (tenafly or wyckoff), every time he fell asleep during one of my recitals, planning what he was going to do with his money when he won the lottery (last I heard I was getting 10%), and every time he told me that I was his princess or koukla or favorite granddaughter. Saying I love you for the last time was one of the hardest things I've had to do but I know he's looking down on us today, smiling as he realizes the beautiful family he has created. I can't wait to play poker with him in heaven, and until then I hope I can live every day making him proud. We love you and will miss you so much Papou, may your memory be eternal.
